In fact, at the beginning, we
didn't want it to be about

00:09:09.640 --> 00:09:10.700
climate change at all.

00:09:10.700 --> 00:09:13.500
We were really considering it
a film about a photographer.

00:09:13.500 --> 00:09:15.430
We called it "The Photographer."
It was about

00:09:15.430 --> 00:09:19.120
James's entire life's work
and a lot of different

00:09:19.120 --> 00:09:20.540
photographic projects
that he had done

00:09:20.540 --> 00:09:21.910
over his whole career.

00:09:21.910 --> 00:09:24.950
And we were using the story of
the ice as a through line,

00:09:24.950 --> 00:09:25.890
effectively.

00:09:25.890 --> 00:09:29.360
And in the editing process, we
realized that we needed to

00:09:29.360 --> 00:09:29.775
shift that.

00:09:29.775 --> 00:09:32.420
And we wanted to switch that
around to make it much more

00:09:32.420 --> 00:09:34.940
focused on the Extreme Ice
Survey and what James

00:09:34.940 --> 00:09:37.260
accomplished with these
time lapses.

00:09:37.260 --> 00:09:40.130
But it brings up the issue of,
how do you communicate climate

00:09:40.130 --> 00:09:41.280
change to the public?

00:09:41.280 --> 00:09:43.080
And this is something that we
spent a lot of time thinking

00:09:43.080 --> 00:09:45.970
about because we didn't want
to approach it as though,

00:09:45.970 --> 00:09:47.210
here's a science-heavy film.

00:09:47.210 --> 00:09:49.350
You're going to sit and be
lectured to and listen to

00:09:49.350 --> 00:09:52.050
experts, talking heads,
about the issue.

00:09:52.050 --> 00:09:55.740
We really tried to frame it in
terms of the adventure and the

00:09:55.740 --> 00:09:57.380
experience that we had.

00:09:57.380 --> 00:09:59.840
Now when we first set
off, that wasn't

00:09:59.840 --> 00:10:01.060
really the goal at all.

00:10:01.060 --> 00:10:03.280
Like I said, we weren't planning
on making a film.

00:10:03.280 --> 00:10:06.370
James wanted to set up these
time-lapse cameras, put them

00:10:06.370 --> 00:10:09.280
out there, and just document
what was going on.

00:10:09.280 --> 00:10:12.500
And I met James when I was
a junior at Stanford.

00:10:12.500 --> 00:10:14.530
The project was getting started
when I was a senior,

